basicPropertyValues.val: The Science Data Discovery Ontology (sddo) is being developed to provide a semantic foundation for the discovery of information managed by NASA's Science Mission Directorate.  This information spans many scientific disciplines, fields and subfields, including heliophysics, earth science, planetary science, astrophysics, biology, astrobiology, and physical science.

comments: PDS data is tricky as while PDS3 has the concept of a data set; PDS4 doesn't really.  You have to find Collections that have a collection_type of data.

definition.val: A PDS data product from the PDS 3 data model.

basicPropertyValues.val: Examples are line plots and spectrograms.

definition.val: A graphical representation of data wherein the underlying numeric values are not (readily) accessible for analysis.

basicPropertyValues.val: Catalogs include lists of events, files in a product, and data availability.

definition.val: A tabular listing of events or observational notes, especially those that have utility in aiding a user in locating data.
Data stored as numerical values in one or more specified formats.
A product from the PDS data system

comments: In the PDS 4 data model, only the collections that have a type of data point directly to data.  Most other types point to other kinds of information products.

definition.val: A PDS data product from the PDS 4 data model.
An interface that 1) presents users with discovery criteria and may 2) lead to an access interface.

comments: Field campaigns are often characterized by in situ terrestrial field work.

definition.val: A campaign that is coordinated among one or more individuals and/or one or more organizations.
A set of experiments and/or observations.

basicPropertyValues.val: For example, the International Halley Watch mobilized observatories around the world for collection of data during the most recent apparition of Comet Halley. The Shoemaker-Levy-9 (SL9) campaign used both Earth-based and spacecraft instruments to monitor the SL9 impact on Jupiter.

definition.val: A campaign that 1) uses primarily but not exclusively existing facilities and 2) after and possibly during which other investigations are carried out using the same facilities.

basicPropertyValues.val: A coronal mass ejection, supernova, earthquake, spacecraft launch, etc.

definition.val: Something observable that happened at a given time and place

basicPropertyValues.val: A single science campaign may require all or part of several missions.
There may be several science campaigns occurring over the course of a single mission.

Morris, Robert, Jennifer Dungan, Lina Khatib, A. Bachman, John Gasch, Paul Hempel, Jenny Williams, Terri Wood, and Christopher Bruno. "Coordinated science campaign planning for earth observing missions." In Proc. of ESTC’04. 2004.

definition.val: A systematic set of activities undertaken to meet a particular science objective.
An assay is an investigative (analytic) procedure for qualitatively assessing or quantitatively measuring the presence, amount, or functional activity of a target entity.

comments: It is generally agreed that data is in the eye of the beholder; but, for the purposes of this project the terms data and data product are limited to traditional mostly numeric science data products that NASA holds and actually calls data or data products. Thus a DataProductService is any product or service that returns science data, normally compiled into a set according to shared characteristics.

definition.val: A product containing science data from some investigation.

comments: Hardware is usually distinguished from the theory and design that make the activity possible.

definition.val: The mechanical, magnetic, electronic, and electrical equipment necessary for conducting an activity.
An originator or creator of a work
A government agency engaged in activities related to outer space and space exploration.

basicPropertyValues.val: A spacecraft, a person, a ship, a piece of laboratory equipment

definition.val: The physical object upon or within which an instrument is mounted.

The quality of a living subject that indicates the taxonomical grouping of the subject.  This grouping can be at any level in a hierachy of organism classification, or a collection of levels, and can be using scientific language or colloquial language.

basicPropertyValues.val: MOD10A1 data files; structured metadata files; data landing page; scientific report; an API that provides search and access to a particular satellite's data; an application for displaying or analyzing data; a movie of a solar flare, images of the MODIS instrument, the Terra satellite, an astronaut, etc.

definition.val: Any offered product or service.
A data product from the GeneLab repository

basicPropertyValues.val: Gender is known to be a factor in the study of high blood pressure.

definition.val: The role played by an entity as part of a scientific investigation such that levels of the measurement or observation of the entity are thought to bear upon the hypotheses being investigated.
A software interface that 1) presents users with selection criteria and 2) presents products or services that meet the criteria the user then selects.

basicPropertyValues.val: For example, a series of related laboratory experiments/observations conducted by a small university team and funded through a single proposal could be an Individual Investigation. Library research by one person on previously published results to distill common conclusions could also be an Individual Investigation.

definition.val: An investigation that 1) uses existing facilities and 2) is under the direction of a single individual.

basicPropertyValues.val: A preparation of tissue or bodily fluid taken for examination or diagnosis.

definition.val: A part of a feature, taken to demonstrate or to determine the character of the whole.
A product that describes some entity.
Hardware used in conducting an experiment.
The realisation of an application, or execution of a plan, idea, model, design, specification, standard, algorithm, or policy.

An information content entity that 1) contains a set of machine-readable instructions (most often in the form of a computer program) that 2) conform to a given syntax (sometimes referred to as a language) that 3) is interpretable by a given processor and that 4) directs a computer's processor to perform specific operations.
A role in which the bearer delivers financial support to enable some activity.

comments: Instrument operating modes may include both hardware configurations (e.g., for instruments with multiple filters) as well as software configurations (e.g., to control how long an exposure should last).  Some instruments have many such modes, others may only have one.

definition.val: An identified configuration for an instrument.

basicPropertyValues.val: For example: (1) the NASA Voyager mission launched two spacecraft to Jupiter and Saturn; (2) the Deep Impact (DI) mission launched a spacecraft, part of which impacted the comet Tempel 2; and (3) the EPOXI mission redefined the objectives of the surviving DI hardware for further exploration of the solar system.

definition.val: An investigation that 1) occupies the designated resources for all (or at least a significant fraction) of the available time and 2) is usually conducted by a national or international space agency using a small number (often one) of spacecraft especially designed and built for the purpose.
Any procedure that involves testing or manipulating a sample or subject in a laboratory setting
An agent that is a human being.

basicPropertyValues.val: Per the NASA SMD glossary at https://science.nasa.gov/glossary/ a mission is a "NASA Science-funded activity with the purpose of meeting goals laid out by presidential directive, and detailed in Science Mission Directorate's strategic plan."  This would mean the ontology would need to include the concepts of a presidential directive and a strategic plan - wait for a use case before implementing this change.

definition.val: A  mission led or funded by NASA

basicPropertyValues.val: A camera, MODIS, a survey instrument (e.g., google form)

definition.val: An instrument is a physical object that can be used to collect data.

basicPropertyValues.val: Added the phrase "plan for a" to the front of the definition per Dan's request

definition.val: A plan for a coordinated set of actions and observations designed to generate data, with the ultimate goal of discovery or hypothesis testing.

comments: While agreed that metadata is just data about data and so is really an unneeded term, we recognize that the term metadata is often applied to information about data no matter its form.  In many cases, a metadata product is available for access, even if the data is not.

definition.val: An information product that contains structured metadata.

basicPropertyValues.val: Mars, a hurricane, the aurora, a molecular cloud, a sunspot, a mouse, its  liver, etc.

comments: Depending on the context, individual entities such as a human or star, may be either features or specimens - depending on whether you are interested in studying the entire class of humans or stars, or a particular star or human.

definition.val: A material entity that has characteristics that can be qualified or quantified through observation or experiment.
A construction, permanent or temporary, on land, in air, space or water, where scientific research or measurements can be undertaken.
A fact or situation that is observed to exist.
Act of carrying out an procedure to estimate or calculate a value of a property of a feature.
A graphical user interface that provides access to photographs/images.
An entity that can bear roles, has members, and has a set of organization rules.

comments: A role which inheres in a person or organization and which is realized during an investigation.

definition.val: A broad framework of goals to be achieved.

basicPropertyValues.val: Journal articles, technical or other reports, books, etc.

comments: May be electronic or physical paper.

definition.val: A written or printed paper that bears the original, official, or legal form of something and can be used to furnish decisive evidence or information.

basicPropertyValues.val: The meaning of a column within a spreadsheet (e.g., identifier or height); the meaning of each pixel in an image (e.g., surface temperature)|another test example

definition.val: A data element is any characteristic that can help in understanding data content. That is, a data element is any parameter or variable that is useful, or critical, when identifying  or describing the content of a data object.
Software that provides the low-level control for a device's specific hardware.
